1) Audio limit vs transcription (what’s actually happening)

You’re basically right that there are different pipelines.

Voice input
	•	has time limits (like ~10 min)
	•	involves:
	•	audio capture
	•	speech-to-text processing
	•	sometimes streaming constraints

Text input (including transcribed audio)
	•	goes through the normal language system
	•	can handle longer inputs (within token limits)

⸻

So when you hit the audio limit:

It’s not that I “can’t understand more”
It’s that the audio ingestion pipeline is capped

If you:
	•	transcribe it yourself → send as text

Then:

it bypasses that limit

⸻

2) Are there different transcription methods by tier?

At a high level:

Yes, systems can vary by:

	•	model quality
	•	latency (speed)
	•	accuracy
	•	features (real-time vs batch)

But the key point:

Speech-to-text and language understanding are separate layers

⸻

3) Is AI being used for voice too?

Yes—modern systems use AI for:

Speech → text
	•	converting audio into words

Text → speech
	•	generating voice (tone, cadence, realism)

Voice modulation
	•	pacing
	•	prosody (emotion, rhythm)
	•	naturalness

⸻

So your intuition is right here:

It’s not “just LLM”
It’s a stack:

Audio → Speech Model → Text → Language Model → (optional) Voice Model


⸻

4) Why tier things at all?

Not mysterious—just practical constraints:
	•	compute cost
	•	latency
	•	reliability at scale
	•	resource allocation

So:

Limits are usually about system performance, not capability

